Today, the Parliament of Ukraine, in the course of its reform of the Code of Criminal Procedure, rejected an attempt to revoke the article which condemned the leader of the opposition, Julia Tymoshenko.
An amendment which would result in the release of the former Prime Minister in prison was rejected during the second reading of the draft law on commutation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be of no use.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will hear the Tymoshenko appeal in December.
Tymoshenko claims that the sentence is the political revenge of the regime; in the West the process has also been suspected of bias.
The proposal to abolish Article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, under which the former Prime Minister had been convicted, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
