More than one third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 are overweight; while 9 per cent of students are overweight, 5 per cent suffer from obesity.
According to a recent study, obese children usually come from unhealthy families.
Once again, we see the importance of the environment and the behaviours accompanying human beings for their or their healthy development.
For example, sausage occurs almost twice as often on tables as in families with children with normal weight.
More than 19% of children suffering from obesity ate fries for dinner on the eve of an educational event called Obesity is not an accident.
Moreover, families of children suffering from obesity do not engage in sports; however, this is true of most families of modern school children; only 15 percent of children say that their parents take time to engage in sports at least once a week.
The study was carried out among 900 children.
The study was carried out at the end of the previous school year; nearly 900 primary students throughout Bohemia participated in it.
The Obesity Event was not an incident carried out for the second consecutive year, with the support of Všeobecná zdravotní pojišovna and Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 students in grades 4 to 8 have joined the project.
Good diet and sufficient sport are the main determinants of the rapidly growing number of children who suffer from either overweight or obesity.
"For example, only half the interviewees said that they eat five meals a day, according to the breakfast- snack-lench-eating-eating scheme, and that's one of the indispensable conditions for proper diet," said one of the conclusions of the study.
No lunch and no sausage at night.
The experts warn that even relative details such as regular family breakfast are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 percent of school families eat breakfast together.
Most families have separate breakfasts.
The worst discovery is that in every tenth family, people don't eat breakfast at all.
And yet breakfast is the basis of the right day's diet.
The study found that fried food is more commonly used in families with children suffering from obesity.
Almost everyone, regardless of weight, drinks sweet cool drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40% of children regularly engage in sports, this figure decreases by more than half, to 15%, when it comes to their parents.
Create your own menu.
In another part of the study, the selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to draw up their own menus based on the products offered and based on their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of Czech children aged 12-15 are far from the ideal of healthy food."
Their favorite food includes a large number of flour, meat, and sweet dishes.
"A particular concern is the great popularity of sweet cooling drinks," says the final part of the study.
As a main meal, the pasta beat a bird with a slight margin.
However, children showed little interest in beans, fish, and vegetables.
Seeking a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also showed that children were prepared to change their eating habits on the condition that they were provided with relevant information.
"Many members of the monitoring group showed a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when they completed the study with obesity -- it's not an accident," said the project.
This was particularly noticeable, for example, in the case of sweet cool drinks -- more children began to prefer them to just water.
In addition, children were more likely to note birds and fish as the main dish, limiting the number of sweet dishes and baking.
