V Need for Speed: Running is happening in America.
Overview
What was supposed to be a careless walk turned into a routine morning trip to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and careless mistakes.
Ambiguities had been satisfied to a certain extent, but that was not important, since no one clearly wanted to do any extra work.
Before the release with a new version of the "Flug" subtitle, there was a lot of hope.
It was expected to move the previous series of Need For Speed in a new direction; demonstration versions showed that the game would take a decent place in the genre of the racing games.
We were curious to see parts of the game where the main character got out of the car and ran.
As is often the case with NFS, in the end much is different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the general impression is corrupted by some unnecessary mistakes that have been present in this series of games for years.
So it's actually not a mistake, it's a demonstration of the inexplicable laziness of the developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You become part of a history whose main hero, Jack, solves some personal problems by participating in an illegal race through America.
You get in a car on the west coast in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
This idea has some interesting features.
The route consists of ten steps divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race takes its own route, and the individual steps take place in a different and interesting environment.
So it doesn't feel like it's the same thing all the time in the game.
Despite the fact that the graph is at the same level as in the previous parts of the series, it's nice to look at some tracks.
And yet the game doesn't give rise to strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, the autumn suburbs, or high in the snowy mountains is a pleasure.
Besides, racing occasionally revives an unusual detail.
In the desert, for example, you fall into a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to get caught in a hole.
Separate races are fairly well organized.
There are only a few species, but that's enough.
For a while you're trying to beat a few opponents (in fact, a normal race); then you're trying to improve the time (standard race with a stopwatch); or you're competing with one adversary.
Besides all that, you occasionally run into a police force that makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not complicated.
Although it is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you would expect (only three to be exact).
In fact, it turns out that it's good for a game because it's not boring; given all the above, it's one of the things that makes the game funnier.
The race model follows the pattern of previous models.
This means that it is no longer something special, but it cannot be considered a disadvantage.
If you're looking for a simulation of real life, you're going to have to look elsewhere.
However, this driving model is very suitable for dynamic racing, although there are better options on the market.
So far, so good.
However, after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not so good.
You don't expect this game to change and crash, but if you have no idea how your car behaves, something's wrong.
Usually, bypassing or passing cars in a dense flow, you sometimes touch the other car slightly, and yet sometimes, in a almost similar situation, your car starts to spin wildly.
Or it's broken.
It's not that important because of the reboot system, but it's enough to ruin fun.
Restarting is done so that if you break up or go far off the track, the game returns you to the point where it was interrupted.
However, only five relaunchs are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start the race from the beginning.
It's useful if something doesn't work out, but you can't totally rely on it.
Sometimes reboots are not enough, and you have to memorize a separate section of the race.
An important disadvantage of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same place.
For example, some turns have to go in a certain way, otherwise you just don't fit in.
In other cases, you meet a civil car in a certain location in the same configuration, whether you come first, fifth, five seconds earlier, or a minute later.
This is particularly frustrating in situations where you see your opponent passing easily between two cars moving in the opposite direction, while when you get there, the machines are already positioned so that you either need to drive around or slow down.
It doesn't matter when you're next to them; it's always happening right in front of you.
The opponents have other advantages.
During the game, you find several places where, regardless of time, the same opponent overtakes you at the same place.
This is particularly evident at the end of the game, on the long bridge where you drive in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent must stand before you no matter what.
The thing is, when he drives in front of you, he makes you look worse, resulting in one or more accidents on this site.
You can understand an attempt to make the game more interesting and filled with adrenaline, but it's so obvious that it's starting to get irritated quickly.
Too bad, because despite the simple model of driving, the game is exciting and sometimes so overwhelmed with events that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
No matter what makes you miss -- a concept with fifty unique tracks, a sequence of races or something.
The idea of changing cars during the race is unusual.
You need to track the gas stations along the way, because that's where your car can switch on, even though in most cases the one you already have is quite enough.
Machines are divided into three categories.
Sport cars are suitable for cities; powerful American cars for direct highway sections; and exotic super-sport car for technical driving, for example on curved mountain routes.
The main story mode is closely associated with the challenge mode; it is a race on individual sites that you will learn during the game.
Here you win for your personal affairs both the coins and the glasses common to the challenges and story regimes.
Many opportunities are available for higher driving, from cars to profile data.
In addition, the profile is related to the Autolog online function, which, among other things, compares your performance with that of other players, and provides communication with the public.
Here's another flaw that's hard to understand; it's an example from the last race in sequence.
You and your car get into the subway tunnel (let's think so) where you run down the tracks in the dark (let's think so).
Your speedometer shows the numbers from 150 to 200 km/h (let's say so) when a train hits you suddenly from behind, turning your car into a pile of scrap metal.
For a few days, our editors talked about whether at the time of the game's creation no one really thought for a second, or whether its creators really thought we were such idiots.
The technical part of the game is nothing special; but the overall impression from the video series is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
While it is a pity that at some critical moments the quality of the record is sometimes rather weakening.
This is particularly true in cases with a large number of players, where a good recording would not really help you either.
Sound is in order; soundtrack is on amateur.
To please as wide a youth audience as possible, the soundtrack's got different styles in it; but it's unlikely that many people will buy a game because of its music.
The general impression of Need for Speed: The escape is rather random.
If the game were to avoid obviously unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that running is the best part of NFS in the last few years.
Anyway, the game leaves a feeling of incompleteness.
Of course, it's a good fun, but prepare yourself for failings to blind you like a spotlight at the airport.
