Evolution of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five government tourist agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: Šedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, the tourist agencies of the time were mostly selling tours to the socialist bloc.
Thus, on vacation Czech tourists travelled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea, on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Bulgaria (Balaton).
The only exception was from 1962 to 1972, when we were able to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which caused considerable restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
A great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovakia citizen wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation was needed from that country; otherwise, an individual journey was impossible.
At the time, tourist agencies offered to travel to the West, but either they had to wait in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or they had to have "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Currency permission was needed to travel to the West, and was not given to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without monetary permission it was not possible to obtain money (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
Most often the Czechs spent their vacations at home, resulting in large numbers of cottages and summer homes, a habit that still exists today.
Since 1989, tourists in the Czech Republic have thus experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989 vacation to the GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our journeys, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox, which we no longer realize, is that before 1989 we could not freely visit Croatia, which is now the most popular one, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the very beginning of 1990 the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring countries in Western Europe was cancelled, resulting in a huge wave of short trips, mostly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakia couldn't afford to go to the West, and everybody wanted to go there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income at the time was scarce for a hotel or boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourists during that period was the desire to bring their own food (conserves, salts, etc.) in order to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, and after decades, our tourists can finally freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income rose, leading to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled tourist agencies to prepare regular flights by charter companies; compared to the past, air travel has now become extremely cheap because of the ability to order bulk discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit nearly all the developed world except the US, which made our journeys even easier.
The next significant event in the history of post-revolution travel occurred in 2000, and the great demand has led to the historic first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have brought Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flight from the Czech Republic will take 12 exotic routes.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our post-revolution development, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US cancelled the requirement for a visa for Czech tourists, and our country has thus permanently joined the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in history in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3 per cent); and for the first time in history, they spent over 15,000 crowns on a person during a foreign vacation, including their destination costs.
