Walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremists in Europe, Anders Bering Bravik was just a guy who spoke out his anti-immigrant views on the Internet.
On Monday, Breiwick, who had confessed to having committed a murder in Norway in July, which had claimed the lives of 77 people, appeared at his first public trial.
Although Braywick could act alone, he was far from alone in the network: he spent a long time preparing to attack behind his computer, interacting with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups in social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy, you just have to go to Facebook.
"We've realized that it's not hard to get close to them," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European cyber populism at the British DEMOS Research Center.
Facebook personal data is so large, says Bartlett that researchers could easily use the site's advertising tool to highlight the necessary population group with scientific precision -- what marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans all over Europe and then gave them advertisements, but instead of showing a new group or a diet product, the advertisement offered the user a survey that included questions about the level of their education, the attitude to violence and the optimism about their own future.
With Facebook's help, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 members of 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries, without even leaving the office.
"It's a completely new way to do research," said Bartlett.
Some of the results are not so amazing: right-wing online players are mostly young men who are dissatisfied with immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online activity with offline activity are smarter, more democratic and less aggressive than those who just hide behind the monitor."
DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook becomes a popular new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and polytologists use the site to study everything in the world, from health issues to social trends expressed in Lycas, wall posts and status updates.
With over 800 million active users adding an average of three entries a day, Facebook's "super-actual information" has caused a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the title of the site by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it provides an opportunity to study people who cannot be reached on the street with a notebook.
"Before, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You would have had to join the party, and they would never have accepted you," said Bartlett.
"Facebook cancels all this -- you address them directly."
Others say that this site could identify and explore social health issues.
A recent study by Dr. Meghan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, and her colleagues showed that students who discussed their drunken Facebook performances were much more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about it.
Moreno suggests that peers, such as their hostel teachers, can monitor the site and intervene to help a student who too often updates drinking status.
"You can't solve the problem without finding it," reported Washington Post Dimitry Christakis, co-author of Moreno and Director of the Centre for Child Health, Behaviour and Development at the Children's Institute of Science and Research in Seattle.
"We've found a way to identify children from a risk group that we wouldn't have found otherwise."
Facebook also regularly extracts various types of data about its users.
The site's data processing team processed the status statistics and Valentine's Day statistics, the mid-term turnout of voters in 2010 and the National happiness index (mainly using information available only to them - the champions of cyber freedom have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching whether they like it or not -- in exchange for playing Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become participants in a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict standards for offline research, online data is publicly available.
"I don't think many users have at least thought that a researcher can monitor their profiles," says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, and he did a study in 2006 using public Facebook pages.
"As far as they thought it was between them and their friends."
This raises the question of the method.
Even offline there's no guarantee that the subject of the study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is not possible to find out how much information in the profile and on the user page is true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do outside Facebook are two completely different things," said Selvin.
That's why, despite his years of work in technology research, Selwin thinks that the notebook and pen are still the best research tools to be used.
"Nothing can replace going to the real world and communicating with real people," he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social research, and most social research is still offline."
