Seven lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview, which is shown in the theatre this week.
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing a technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans can think of as the greatest discovery in the recently discovered interview, which was remembered in anticipation of the pre-shows at the main markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood in business processes and production technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a careful organizer and modernizer of the production process, who believed that many business leaders had suffered from "the pain of thinking that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] the great idea of a great product separates a great amount of skill."
Let's go back to 1995, Bob Kringley was creating a TV series called the Nerde Triumph on the arrival of a personal computer, and he spent over an hour with Jobs for a uniquely long conversation.
By that time, it had been about 10 years since Jobs was banished from Apple, and he was already fully employed by his new NeXT computer company in anticipation of the massive development of the Internet.
While a small part of Kringley's interview was used in the Nards, he says that the original interviews were missing during transport.
Only after Jobs' death was a full VHS copy found in the director's garage.
This film, which was somewhat edited, became the basis for the 68-minute film, Steve Jobs: Lost interview, which is published on Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hate for detailed interviews, Jobs seems here unusually prepared to express his technological philosophy and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
At four different moments during the interview, there's a great deal of time between questions and answers -- reflections for 10-15 seconds, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to be more precise.
There are also moments where Jobs' perfection comes to the surface, where he seems irritated by Kringley's questions, which make him move quickly to issues or events of greater importance.
