The court will approve the " digital television transition" in Mexico in 2015
Changing analogues to digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court (JC) rejected the constitutional motions made by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential decree, which moved the so-called digital television transition from 2021 to 2015, as eight votes were not obtained to cancel it.
A minority of four Ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderon had not exceeded his authority by issuing a decree detailing the steps taken to move to digital ground television.
As a result, the constitutional claims submitted by the Senate were rejected because of the absence of a qualified majority of the eight votes required for the court to pronounce on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree and it remains in force.
The draft declaration, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, suggested that the decree be declared unconstitutional because the regulation of the radio and television programme is a right established by law for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legal reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Marguerite Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this ground, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional discussions to challenge the decree and support complaints, and Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions mentioned in it concerning the transition to digital broadcasting.
It was also decided at the meeting to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the draft in that the Federal Executive could not determine the general rules for the measures to be prepared by the public administration.
“I also do not believe that if this were the case, it would affect the autonomy of the regulating body” and recalled that planning public policies in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, has to do with the Federal Executive, which has a constitutional mandate, government.
Replacement of analogues with digital signals, one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years, has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of transformation into digital form, which includes meeting public needs that have not only a technical dimension, “because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues”.
These issues, he said, “requests the work of the entire system of public economic management to include a group of authorities which the Constitution unites into the State Executive”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the digital broadcasting process and had done so with the help of the Executive, despite the existence of highly specialized technical institutions.
From this it cannot be concluded that the Government, by passing the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of the Congress, ensures, in the administrative sphere, the observance of the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
In Michoacana, an analysis is made of the possibility of counting "voice-to-voice"
According to data submitted to the PRRA, the difference between the first and second seats in the governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes of 879 out of a total of 6.074 protocols.
The possibility of counting the “vote-by-vote” process this year in Michoacán is real, where, according to the Preliminary Results Program (PPP), the difference between the first and second seats in the governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting 879 of the total of 6.074 protocols.
In the light of this, the President of the General Council of the Michokan Election Institute (IVM), Maria de Los Angeles Landeral Saragos, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the Election Corps adopted a set of principles to align local rules with the federal election reform.
It should be borne in mind that Michoacán did not accept the Constitution or the State Election Code or the Voting Rights Act, as the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal time frame for their entry into force in this election process and that the Governor, Léonel Godoy Rangel, did not include its publication within the time frame set by the Act in the Official Gazette of the State, arguing that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (JJJ) decided on a constitutional claim submitted by the local legislature and called the state's representative's vote on constitutional reform “unvalid and illegal” because it had no right to “permit or support them”.
In an interview on the possibility of a "voice for vote," Mary de Los Angeles Landerall argued that, with the adoption of suitable principles by the General Council of IWM, it would be possible to present a partial or complete counting of votes by the local election body.
For example, a partial recalculation of one or more voting urns may be made under the conditions that: the results of the protocols do not match; there is no record of voting and the counting of documents in the urn or it is not in the hands of the chairman; or there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, the total recalculation of votes in all the urns in the elections may take place when there is a sign that the difference between the alleged winner of the elections in question and the second-place candidate is less than or equal to 1 per cent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from the representative of the party and/or the coalition who has submitted the second of those candidates.
The total recalculation of votes will also be made if at the end of the normal counting it is determined that the difference between the winner and the second-place candidate is less than or equal to 1 per cent, provided that there is a request from a political party whose candidate has second-placed, in the event that the voting boxes which have been considered in partial recalculation are excluded.
It is worth noting that this is the case with the Morelia elections, where according to PDRP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16 per cent, even if there are no 129 votes out of a total of 923 protocols.
