A new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to introduce a new government that will face the crisis that put this country on the verge of an economic catastrophe.
The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet with the Italian President on Wednesday to introduce a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the verge of an economic catastrophe and has damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the Presidential Palace stated that Monty, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the President, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he could form a government.
He was expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it was not clear when the new executive branch would take up its positions.
Monty said that he would present to the President the results of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to prove my complete confidence in our country's ability to get out of this difficult period," said the former European commissioner to reporters.
Monty did not explicitly say that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that obstacles had been overcome.
"The artwork is now well marked," he said.
Monty completed the government formation process in less than three days, much less than usual, because Italy was struggling with the political and financial crisis, which brought their debt to a critical level.
The administration, under the leadership of former European commissioner Monty, must approve the austerity package required by European leaders in order to regain confidence in Italy.
On the basis of pressure on Monty to hurry, unstable markets have set up revenue from the BTP bonds of Italy for 10 years over 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to save.
Emma Marchegalia, leader of the Italian employers' Federation, informed reporters after meeting with Monty, "We said we would actively support this government."
We believe that this government is Italy's last chance to get out of this critical situation.
Monty's chances of success were largely based on the support of the LDP party Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to retire on Saturday because of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monty's efforts should lead to a good result," said Angelino Alphano, secretary of the Central-Right Party.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important because so far many of its members have resisted the government majority of technocrats that form Monty.
Parliamentary support
The new Monty government must have strong parliamentary support for reform, which will probably be unpopular reforms of austerity.
Any blocking or suspending of these attempts can lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
An Italian association of foreign banks has increased pressure, warning that Monty's failure can be a disaster.
Monty began his consultations on Monday with political parties, associations and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations.
He'll finish a series of his meetings on Tuesday night.
Monty was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who resolved a very rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a short break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would retire, the value of Italy's debt had now reached a critical level, given the uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister would be successful.
Salvaging Italy with a government debt of Euro1.8 billion would be too much for modern euro-zone financial advocates.
Monty said that his government would exist until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to reform before he ordered a new election.
Monty said he wanted politicians to be included in his cabinet, but the main parties insisted that it should be composed only of technical experts, evidence of their dissatisfaction with the financial situation affecting the process.
Political sources reported that the mutual mistrust and opposition of the parties made it more difficult to attempt to include political figures.
