If attention had been paid to the signals sent by the road cover, it would have been necessary to repair about 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the Mexico City Valley, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM Chemical Faculty, and adds that if the process of construction and maintenance of the asphalted road surface is correct, the number of pits may be reduced or even reduced to zero.
In his lecture, the Technical View of the pits, read during the International Year of Chemistry, reported that the laboratory for which it is responsible is developing polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mixture of characteristics close to the bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperature.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, in order to improve the quality of roads and therefore resist the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the hardest part of oil, is the sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some are the high molecular mass, called asphalt, and others are the low molecular mass, called maltens, which together provide road cover for its distinctive viscosity.
The viscosity of the bitumen is the fact that in high temperatures about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it keeps almost solid, while at very low temperature the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance of the street asphalt is not constant, but changes during the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, by a specialist in chemical engineering.
The chemist observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexibly covered, composed of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the top layers is a bitumen composed of small stones, put into bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that forms this surface, he said, is sunk in bitumen.
When driving and applying effort, this helps the forces to be very well distributed on the road surface.
If it were modified asphalt, they'd be even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt cover, he added, placed the last layer, called the dew layer, which is made of small stones, actually sand also dipped into asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will be in contact with the wheels of transport, it must have more resistance than asphalt cover and provide for road friction.
As part of the road surface which will receive and disseminate these forces, the wear layer also requires the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
The weather, especially the humidity and temperature variations, are also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it has a significant effect on the condition of asphalt.
When the ground is raw, the water penetrates the surface and it's hard to get out of there, it makes all the layers of the surface softened and hence the formation of a pit.
When forming a pit, he said, the first thing to wear is the dew layer and then it affects the bitumen, but the damage doesn't happen instantly, which is a process that should be taken into account at the first signs of maintenance programs.
A member of the National Research System also explained that transport is another important factor in creating holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer must always be linked to the transport burden and must be guaranteed to meet this requirement in order to prevent the frequent occurrence of pits.
Rafael Herrera said that relatively bitumen still needs to be studied and done, for example, with the bitumen emulsions that are already on the market in other countries and even help to fix holes easily and without the use of high temperature.
